eral retinal traction. Retinal detachment is a relatively common complication in Wagner disease, the reported incidence rate varying from 7% to 50%. In a few patients, rhegmatogenous retinal detachment is due to flap tears or atrophic holes and occurs typically at a young age. More frequently, peripheral tractional retinal detachment is observed, occuring typically in middle-aged patients. In some cases, anterior chamber angle dysgenesis is observed.", "etiology": "Wagner disease is a connective tissue disorder affecting the collagen and is associated with mutations in the CSPG2 or VCAN gene (5q13-q14). CSPG2 encodes chondroitin sulfate proteoglycan-2, also known as versican. Versican constitutes 5-15% of the total protein content of the vitreous gel. It is a large proteoglycan that forms large complexes by binding to hyaluronic acid and other vitreous structural molecules. Erosive vitreoretinopathy (ERVR), originally described as a distinct clinical entity, is an allelic disease, and the same intronic mutation in GSPG2 has been found in a family with ERVR and four families with Wagner disease.", "diagnostic_methods": "Diagnosis is based on the clinical picture. Molecular testing of CSPG2 mutations confirms the diagnosis.", "differential_diagnosis": "Differential diagnosis includes Stickler syndrome, Goldmann-Favre disease, Familial Exudative Vitreoretinopahy, and Autosomal Dominant Vitreoretinochoroidopathy (ADVIRC) (see these terms).", "genetic_counseling": "Wagner disease is inherited as an autosomal dominant trait with near complete penetrance but variable expressivity.", "management_and_treatment": "Regular ophthalmologic examinations should be performed. Retinal breaks without retinal detachment are treated by prophylactic laser- or cryocoagulation. For rhegmatogenous retinal detachment in a young patient, scleral buckling surgery or, less often, vitrectomy is performed. Tractional retinal detachment in the middle-aged or elderly patient requires often a combined procedure. Presenile cataract is treated by phacoemulsification and implantation of an artificial intraocular lens.", "prognosis": "Overall prognosis seems to be moderate. In the original pedigree described by Wagner, about 50% of the affected members retained a useful vision of more than 20/40 after the age of 60."}, {"name": "Degner-Syndrom", "sub_name": "Oro-fazio-digitales Syndrom Typ 13", "english": 0, "defenition": "Ein seltener Subtyp des Oro-fazio-digitales Syndroms, der sporadisch auftritt und durch kardiale (Mitral- und Trikuspidalklappendysplasie) und neuropsychiatrische Manifestationen (Epilepsie, Depression) sowie orale, faziale und digitale Fehlbildungen (linguale Hamartome, Lippenspalte, Brachydaktylie, Klinodaktylie, Syndaktylie der H\u00e4nde und F\u00fc\u00dfe) gekennzeichnet ist. Ebenfalls assoziiert ist eine Leukoaraiose, die bei der MRT-Untersuchung des Gehirns erkennbar wird.", "synonyms": "Degner-Syndrom, OFD13, Oral-fazial-digitales Syndrom Typ 13, ", "prevalence": "<1 / 1 000 000", "age_of_onset": "Neugeborenenzeit", "ICD-10": "Q87.0", "UMLS": "C2932680", "MeSH": "C548035", "GARD": "10694"}, {"name": "Degos-Krankheit", "sub_name": "Papulose, atrophische maligne", "english": 0, "defenition": "Die Atrophische maligne Papulose (MAP) ist eine seltene, chronische, thrombo-obliterative Vaskulopathie, die durch papul\u00f6se Hautl\u00e4sionen mit zentraler porzellanwei\u00dfer Atrophie und einem umgebenden teleangiektatischen Rand gekennzeichnet ist. Systemische L\u00e4sionen k\u00f6nnen den Magen-Darm-Trakt und das zentrale Nervensystem (ZNS) befallen und sind potenziell letal.", "synonyms": "Degos-Krankheit, Kohlmeier-Degos-Krankheit, K\u00f6hlmeier-Degos-Delort-Tricort-Syndrom, Papulosis maligna atrophicans, ", "prevalence": "<1 / 1 000 000", "inheritance": "Autosomal-dominant\u00a0", "age_of_onset": "Erwachsenenalter", "ICD-10": "I77.8", "OMIM": "602248", "UMLS": "C0221011", "MeSH": "D054853", "GARD": "6249", "MedDRA": "10064281", "epidemio