er in Momenten, in denen sich der Patient nicht beobachtet f\u00fchlt. H\u00e4ufig ist die PMD mit anderen psychogenen Symptomen kombiniert, z.B. simulierte Schw\u00e4che, sensorische Zeichen oder \u00fcbergro\u00dfe Schmerzen. Depression und Angst sind h\u00e4ufig. Die PMD f\u00e4llt in eine von drei Kategorien: Somatoforme Krankheiten, Artefakt-Krankheiten und Simulation. Die somatoformen Krankheiten umfassen Konversionskrankheiten und Somatisationen. Zu den Artefakt-Krankheiten werden willentlich, zum Zweck eines psychologischen Gewinns produzierte Symptome gez\u00e4hlt. Unter Simulation wird das willentliche Produzieren von Symptomen zum Zweck eines materiellen Gewinns verstanden. Die Diagnose wird zumeist klinischgestellt, aber gewisse zus\u00e4tzliche Tests k\u00f6nnen hilfreich sein. Mittels Elektromyographie (EMG) k\u00f6nnen psychogener Tremor und psychogener Myoklonus von ihren organischen Gegenst\u00fccken unterschieden werden. Bildgebende Verfahren in Form von [123J]Beta-CIT-SPECT und [18F]DOPA-PET werden gelegentlich bei schwierig zu diagnostizierendem psychogenem Parkinsonismus angewendet, um eine organische Verursachung auszuschlie\u00dfen. Kriterien einer guten Betreuung sind das Vermeiden iatrogener Sch\u00e4den, unn\u00f6tiger invasiver Tests und unpassender Medikamente, sowie die Vermittlung einer angemessenen psychiatrischen Behandlung. Klinische Studien sind selten, aber in der Literatur gibt es Hinweise, dass die Kombination einer Psychotherapie mit individualisierter Gabe von Psychopharmaka (zur Therapie begleitender Zust\u00e4nde, wie Depression oder Angst) hilfreich sein kann. Die Prognose eine PMD ist unterschiedlich, aber besser als bei Patienten mit anderen somatoformen Beschwerden, z.B. sensorischen Symptomen, Schw\u00e4che oder Schmerzen. Eine eventuelle psychiatrische Komorbidit\u00e4t (Depression oder Angstkrankheit) ist ein prognostisch g\u00fcnstiger Faktor. Prognostisch ung\u00fcnstige Faktoren sind: Bereits langfristig bestehende Symptome, pl\u00f6tzlicher Beginn der Bewegungsst\u00f6rung, die prim\u00e4re psychiatrische Diagnose einer Hypochondrie, eine Artefakt-Krankheit oder Simulation. Unbehandelt neigt die PMD zur Chronifizierung, bei verschiedenen Nachuntersuchungen zeigten 65-95% der Patienten bleibende Symptome.", "english": 1, "defenition": "A rare neurologic disease characterized by the manifestation of an underlying psychiatric illness or malingering, and that cannot be attributed to any known structural or neurochemical diseases. Most cases fall in the psychiatric diagnostic category of conversion disorder, also referred to as functional neurological symptom disorder.", "synonyms": "Psychogenic dystonia, ", "prevalence": "Unknown", "inheritance": "Not applicable\u00a0", "age_of_onset": "Childhood, Adolescent, Adult, Elderly", "icd_10": "F44.4", "umls": "C3267131", "meddra": "10072376", "epidemiology": "The exact prevalence of psychogenic movement disorders (PMD) is unknown. At tertiary care centers, 2-4% of movement disorders patients are diagnosed with PMD.", "clinical_description": "PMD present typically during adolescence or adulthood. Childhood cases and new onset in the elderly are rare, but do occur. Symptoms may include one or several types of abnormal movements seen in organic movement disorders (tremor, dystonia, chorea, bradykinesia, myoclonus, tics, athetosis, ballism, cerebellar incoordination), and also affect speech and gait. Typically, PMD present with complex movements of multiple different phenomenologies, usually incongruent with an organic movement disorder and affecting several body regions. Tremor appears to be the most commonly observed phenomenon, followed by dystonia, bradykinesia, myoclonus, and other unclassifiable abnormal movements. Symptoms often occur abruptly, and maximal symptom severity and disability are reached quickly. Other typical features are: deliberate slowness of movement, distractibility, variability, suggestibility, paroxysmal symptoms, and resolution with placebo administration or when the patient is unaware of being observed. Frequently, PMD are accompanied by other psychogenic symptoms such as false weakness, sensory findings, or excessive pain. Depression and anxiety are common comorbidities.", "etiology": "Underlying causes for PMD fall into three categories: Conversion disorder (also referred to as functional neurological symptom disorder), somatic symptom disorders, or, in rare cases, factitious disorder, and malingering. Risk factors include female gender, history of childhood trauma or sexual abuse, previous injury, surgery, and major stressful life events.", "diagnostic_methods": "The diagnosis is usually made on clinical grounds, but certain ancillary tests may be helpful. Electromyography-based tremor and myoclonus analysis can be used to distinguish psychogenic tremor and myoclonus from their organic counterparts. Neuroimaging in the form of [123 I]-beta-CIT SPECT and [18F]-DOPA-PET is sometimes used in difficult to diagnose cases of psychogenic parkinsonism to exclude an organic etiology.", "differential_diagnosis": "The differential diagnosis of PMD lies in the organic counterparts of each individual presenting abnormal movement. In cases of tremor as the presenting symptom for example, Parkinson's disease and essential tremor will be considered. Some patients with PMD have movements that resemble seizures, and epilepsy should be ruled out.", "antenatal_diagnosis": "Prenatal diagnosis does not exist for this disorder.", "management_and_treatment": "Avoidance of iatrogenic damage by unnecessary invasive tests or inappropriate medications, early and precise diagnosis, and the facilitation of the appropriate psychiatric and physical rehabilitation treatment are important. Clinical trials are sparse, but the available literature suggests that a combination of psychotherapy with individualized psychiatric medication (aimed at treating coexisting conditions such as depression or anxiety) may be beneficial. Some centers also offer interdisciplinary inpatient programs, combing intense physiotherapy with psychotherapy.", "prognosis": "The prognosis of PMD is variable, but is better than that for patients with other somatoform complaints such as sensory symptoms, weakness or pain. The presence of psychiatric comorbidity (depression or an anxiety disorder) is a positive prognostic factor. Long-standing symptoms, insidious onset of movements and primary psychiatric diagnosis of hypochondriasis, a factitious disorder, or malingering are negative prognostic factors. If left untreated, PMD tend to be chronic, and follow-up data in several series show persistent symptoms in 65-95% of patients."}, {"name": "Dystonie, reine", "sub_name": "Dystonie, isolierte", "english": 0, "defenition": "Zusatzinformationen\n", "synonyms": "Dystonie, reine, ", "ICD-10": "G24.1", "summary": "Dieser Terminus bezieht sich auf eine Krankheitsgruppe. Bitte nutzen Sie das Menu Klassifikation, um mehr \u00fcber die Krankheiten zu erfahren, die sich unter diesem Sammelbegriff zusammenfassen lassen."}, {"name": "Dystroglykanopathie", "sub_name": "Alpha-Dystroglykan, qualitative oder quantitative Defekte", "english": 0, "defenition": "Unsere Website hostet keinerlei Werbung\nUnsere Partnerschaften beeinflussen in keiner Weise unsere Ver\u00f6ffentlichungspolitik\n", "synonyms": "Alpha-Dystroglykanopathie, Dystroglykanopathie, ", "ICD-10": "G71.2", "UMLS": "C2936406", "summary": "Dieser Terminus bezieht sich auf eine Krankheitsgruppe. Bitte nutzen Sie das Menu Klassifikation, um mehr \u00fcber die Krankheiten zu erfahren, die sich unter diesem Sammelbegriff zusammenfassen lassen."}, {"name": "Dystroglykanopathie, prim\u00e4re", "sub_name": "Prim\u00e4re qualitative oder quantitative Alpha-Dystroglykan-Defekte", "english": 0, "defenition": "Unsere Website hostet keinerlei Werbung\nUnsere Partnerschaften beeinflussen in keiner Weise unsere Ver\u00f6ffentlichungspolitik\n", "synonyms": "Alp